class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-281"><div
id="comment-281"><div
class="gravatar"> <img
alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/4ae4cf782e771e10854dec2e07c647db?s=36&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D36&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-36 photo' height='36' width='36' /></div><div
class='comment_content'> <cite
class="author_name heading"><a
href='http://www.facebook.com/people/Ralf-Rottmann/725299921' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Ralf Rottmann</a></cite> <span
class="says">says:</span><div
class="comment-meta commentmetadata"> <a
href="http://rottmann.net/2009/11/federate-google-wave-sandbox-with-your-own-fedone-server/comment-page-1/#comment-281">09/11/2009 at 21:02</a></div><div
class='comment_text entry-content'><p>Taken from some excellent comments on James Purser&#8217;s blog (<a
href="http://jamespurser.com.au/blog/Federating_Your_Wave_Server" rel="nofollow">http://jamespurser.com.au/blog/Federating_Your_Wave_Server</a>), I also recommend, to disable Openfire&#8217;s pubsub and group chat features, as they might interfere with the way FedOne discovers XMPP services.</p><p>Disable Openfire pubsub service:<br
/> - Go to Server Manager > System Properties. Scroll down to the bottom and enter the following information:<br
/> Property Name: xmpp.pubsub.enabled<br
/> Property Value: false</p><p>Disabling Openfire Group Chat:<br
/> - Go to Group Chat > Group Chat Settings<br
/> - Delete the &#8220;conference&#8221; domain</p><p>Once you have completed these steps restart the Openfire service (sudo /etc/init.d/openfire restart).</p><p>Thanks James!</p> <a
class='comment-reply-link' href='/2009/11/federate-google-wave-sandbox-with-your-own-fedone-server/?replytocom=281&PHPSESSID=4363386b351b0eff52a555a88a928f0c#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-281", "281", "respond", "1043")'>Reply</a></div></div></div></li><li
